Subsidy trap
America Cambridge — No policy is more directly at odds between good economics and good politics than food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue faced by the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidy cuts that Sisi faces are better than expected.
On the contrary, Modi is facing a worse situation than expected, potentially even undermining the long-anticipated World Trade Organization agreement.
While Joko Widodo's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved what few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have managed to accomplish: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41–78%.
Surprisingly, there were almost no protests of opposition.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and also urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained extremely low, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies have often sparked unrest, even toppling governments.
But the Sisi government seems to be making progress in this area.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sisi had no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year reached 10% of GDP (it would have been 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, few expected that Xi Xi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, could act more swiftly than Modi. Modi became Prime Minister of India, where there was a overwhelming democratic majority, in his urgent desire for comprehensive economic reform.
In Indonesia, Joko Widodo, who took office in October, inherited long-standing fuel subsidies amounting to as high as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), which had already placed a heavy burden on the country.
Susilo, who had stepped down, had already taken a brave first step a year earlier by raising fuel prices.
Joko Widodo's advisors suggested cutting the remaining subsidies, and he himself frankly stated that the plan would be implemented gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, as agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive areas, the government — rather than large private monopolies — is the root cause.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
Food and fossil fuel subsidies have sparked sharp controversy because they are often promoted under the banners of environmental or equality concerns, but in reality, they fail to achieve these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies go to the poorest population, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the wealthiest.
Globally, far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government, which sought to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
In fact, Modi's government vetoed the WTO compromise, undoing the most significant progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies can sometimes benefit producers by allowing consumers to benefit, especially in poor countries; and sometimes benefit consumers by allowing producers to benefit, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to do both.
As a result, India achieved a feat: distributing wheat to consumers at artificially low prices, while at the same time experiencing surplus supply, because farmers could receive high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs — electricity, water, and fertilizers — which have damaged the environment.
) The government purchased large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, and the way consumers received only a small portion of the distribution was both corrupt and failed to help the poor.
The government may continue to provide subsidies and maintain stockpiles.
But it knows that this would violate WTO rules.
Since it cannot permanently change these rules, Modi simply rejected the Trade Facilitation Agreement, which the WTO had eagerly anticipated.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to withdraw them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did in the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot isolate them from shocks.
But people accustomed to government-set prices for food and energy will demand the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument for not implementing subsidies from the beginning.
However, this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining them is necessarily the best choice for savvy politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap eventually leads to even larger retail price hikes, slow-moving leaders will not benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, while cutting food and energy subsidies, other more efficient measures to support the bottom income groups should be adopted.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's conditional cash transfer program Progresa-Oportunidades, Brazil's Bolsa Família program, and India's Unique Identification system, which represent innovations in both policy and technology.
However, some countries are forced to make adjustments only when a budget crisis occurs, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate the pain.
Prudent politicians might instead implement unpopular adjustments right at the beginning of their tenure.
Jokowi and Sisi both adopted this approach.
Modi, who won the election with a mandate for market reforms, has fallen behind.
